3/x) It broke my heart. He's the sweetest young guy. Over the past few months, I've been doing an intense cleaning out/organizing at my mom's house. I found so many old traffic tickets of my father's. At first I thought it was kind of funny. #BLM

4/x) But the sheer number was odd. When I looked at some of them closer, the speed was never fast. I realized he was probably getting pulled over so often because he was a Black man. I was so angry and hurt realizing this. #BLM

16/x) Personally my overall experience with police officers in Bridgewater has been good. Some of them have been very kind.  But I'm also a woman and rather short. For men it can be very different. Hopefully I made a positive difference yesterday. #BLM

5/x) Thinking about my cousin and father, I had to do something when I saw that young Black man. It was safe for me to pull over, park my car, then walk over to observe the situation. I stayed across the street for my own safety. #BLM

12/x) The young man was sitting on the ground at this point. He was never restrained and the situation seemed to remain calm. The officers were just talking to him. Then all the officers got in their cruisers and left. #BLM

11/x) The officer asked me if I knew the guy. I said no, but I just wanted to make sure that he was okay. The officer said that they wanted to make sure he was okay as well and he crossed the street again. #BLM

14/x) If he were having some sort of mental issue, I was not equipped to handle it. But I was glad that I pulled over. I didn't really do anything except observe. But maybe that was enough to keep the situation calm. #BLM
13/x) I started walking back to my car and the young man walked in the other direction. Still with no shirt on. Which seemed a bit off, so I decided not to speak with him after this encounter. #BLM

15/x) Before I arrived, a third officer had been called. It seemed they were prepared to escalate the situation. Maybe things would have happened differently if I had not been there watching. I'll never know. But I'm glad that I pulled over. #BLM

10/x) As I was talking to her explaining what was happening, one of the officers crossed the street and was approaching me. I explained this to her so that the officer could hear that I was telling someone in real time what was happening. #BLM

8/x) This was just one guy. Why did they need three police officers? If he were white would they have three officers? I figured I should call someone to let them know what was going on in case something happened. #BLM

1/x) The news here today seems worse than usual. Maybe my experience may encourage others. Also, I need to write about this police encounter to process it fully. Yesterday, I was leaving my mom's house in Bridgewater and had almost reached the highway. #BLM

17/end) With all that's happening in the world, don't underestimate the difference one small gesture can make. As @LesterHoltNBC
 says, "Please take care of yourself ‚Ä¶ and each other.‚Äù #BLM #StopAsianHate

6/x) But I wanted the police officers to see that I was watching them. I also wanted that young man to see that another Black person was seeing what was happening to him. For a few minutes I just stood there looking across the road at them. #BLM

7/x) It was about 4pm on Route 104 and busy with traffic. Lots of cars on both sides and backed up on the side where the two police cruisers were parked. Another police cruiser sped by and turned around joining the other two officers. #BLM

2/x) I saw a very young Black man with no shirt on the other side of the street with two police officers questioning him. Years ago, my cousin moved to Bridgewater. He was stopped by the police so often he couldn't take it anymore and moved away. #BLM
9/x) I called a close family friend in Bridgewater. She's  very active in the community and local politics. She's also the cousin of the late civil rights icon John Lewis. #BLM
